display.shortDescription: An easy starter profile to make something tasty for milk drinks.
display.description: A flow profile in the same style as the similarly named default profile on Decent machines.  It was intended to target good espresso shots for milk drinks while being tolerant of 'not-yet-very-good barista technique'.  The hold flow rate should be between 1.2-2.0ml/s with 1.2 targeted at dark roast and 2.0 max for light. The default target pressure cap is a bit below 9 bar per the original profile design, but you can also adjust it any where in the 5-9 bar range if you find the milder extraction yields better results for your pallet.  The original profile guidance suggested that you need to grind fine enough to allow building up to the target 6-9 bar peak pressure going in the hold stage.  Ideally the pressure curve should then decline linearly when you're in the hold stage as the puck erodes.  If the pressure falls off dramatically it may be indicative of channeling.  A properly linear pressure fall-off graph will clue you into the yield where the majority of extraction has completed where the curve begins to flatten and the lower pressure begins to hold at the steady hold flow-rate; this can inform where you'd like to set the yield target for that bean/grind combo.  You can see an example of this style pulled on a Decent using medium-light beans at https://www.youtube.com/live/LZHmXSqMGHg?si=vSLD53pEc0sQPI64&t=1160
